Exoplanet Data

We will be working with data on exoplanets; exoplanets are planets orbiting stars outside our Solar System. The data were pulled from the NASA Exoplanet Archive on September 12, 2022.

The variables we will be working with are defined below. If you want more details, please see the exoplanet archive data column definitions (using the column names in the raw data).

planet = Planet Name method = Method by which the planet was first identified year = Discovery Year (the year it was discovered) number = Number of Planets radius = Planet Radius (units: Earth Radius) mass = Approximate or Minimum Planet Mass (units: Earth Mass)

Questions

Question 1

Make a scatter plot with radius (the estimate of the planet radius) on the x-axis and mass (the estimate of the planet mass) on the vertical axis. The scale_y_log10() and scale_y_log10() are added to change the axis values to a log10() scale.

## COMPLETE CODE TO MAKE THIS PLOT
ggplot(planets, aes(x=radius, y=mass)) + geom_point() +
  scale_y_log10() + scale_x_log10() +
  xlab("Radius (earth radius)") + ylab("Mass (earth mass)") +
  ggtitle("Exoplanets mass vs. radius",
          subtitle="Using NASA explanet archive data")

Question 2

Make a scatter plot like the previous problem, but add the color aesthetic inside the aes() function and set it equal to method (discovery method). This will color each point according to which method was used to discover it.

## COMPLETE CODE TO MAKE THIS PLOT
ggplot(planets, aes(x=radius, y=mass, color=method)) + geom_point() +
  scale_y_log10() + scale_x_log10() +
  xlab("Radius (earth radius)") + ylab("Mass (earth mass)") +
  ggtitle("Exoplanets mass vs. radius",
          subtitle="Using NASA explanet archive data")

Question 3

Make a barplot counting how many planets were discovered using each method. (Hint: use geom_bar(), which counts the number of occurences, unlike geom_col()).

## COMPLETE CODE TO MAKE THIS PLOT
ggplot(planets, aes(x=method)) + geom_bar()

  xlab("Method") + ylab("Count") +
  ggtitle("Number of discoveries by method",
          subtitle="Using NASA explanet archive data")
## Error in xlab("Method") + ylab("Count"): non-numeric argument to binary operator

Question 4

  • Which discovery method was used to detect the most exoplanets in our planet data frame? Transit was overwhelmingly used.
  • What general pattern do you notice between planet mass and radius? Radius and mass show a positive linear correlation.
  • What is the estimated radius (approximately) of the most massive planet included on the plot? 12.4
largest_value = planets %>% 
  arrange(desc(mass)) %>%
  slice_head(n = 10)

Question 5

Make a histogram showing the distribution of the base-10 log of the masses in the dataset. Note you can do this by setting log10(mass) as the x aesthetic inside aes(). Pick a nice fill and color for the histogram. Looking at the plot visually, what’s the approximate mean log mass? ~2

## COMPLETE CODE TO MAKE THIS PLOT
ggplot(planets, aes(x=log10(mass))) + geom_histogram(color="red", fill="white") +
  xlab("Mass") + ylab("Count") +
  ggtitle("Histogram of log masses of exoplanets",
          subtitle="Using NASA explanet archive data")
